We know that it must have been hourly a greater pain to him than any sight of intolerable wrong or shame has ever been for a transient period to us. It is clear, then, that he perceived some very grave reason for abstaining from direct effort against secular abuses.

The “ repentance ” preached by Jesus and his messengers was evidently one in which the turning from evil habits bore only an incidental, though necessary, part, for when he upbraids those who refuse to repent, it is their lack of faith, their deadness to the miracles of mercy performed in their midst‚ which he quotes as their sin. If his preaching had resembled that of the Rabbis, or of that higher product of Judaism‚ the Baptist‚ the reason he would have given for rejection would have been love of sin.
